'''Tsukiyomi Shrine''' (月讀神社, ''Tsukiyomi jinja'') is a [[Shinto]] shrine located in [[Nishikyō-ku, Kyoto|Nishikyō Ward]], [[Kyoto]], Japan. It was named in an ancient Japanese religious book ''[[Engishiki]]'' as a Myōjin Taisha ({{Jp|Great shrine for notable god|名神大社}}). The shrine is currently a subsidiary shrine of [[Matsunoo Taisha]].
Tsukiyomi Shrine is one of the "Matsuo Seven Shrines". Its annual festival is on October 3.
== Enshrined deity == The shrine is dedicated to [[Tsukuyomi-no-Mikoto]] {{Jp|2=ツクヨミノミコト, 月読命}}, the moon god in traditional Japanese mythology. Generally, Tsukuyomi is known as the brother of the sun god [[Amaterasu]] {{Jp|2=天照大御神}}, as noted in both ''[[Kojiki]]'' and ''[[Nihon Shoki]]''. However, the legend passed down in Tsukiyomi Shrine is different from the version found in ''Kojiki''. According to ''Nihon Shoki'', which recorded the shrine's founding in the February article of the 3rd year of [[Emperor Kenzō]], "Tsukigami", the decedent of [[Takamimusubi]] {{Jp|2=高御産巣日神}}, is the lord of Iki Prefecture {{Jp|2=壱岐県}}. In addition, in ''Sendai Kuji Hongi'' {{Jp|2=先代旧事本紀}}, the deity appeared to be the ancestor of Iki Prefecture with the divine name of "Amagetsu no Mikoto" {{Jp|2=天月神命}}.<ref name=":2">{{Cite book |last=Matsumae |first=Takeshi |url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/237474432 |title=Nihon shinwa no nazo ga yoku wakaru hon |last2=松前健 |date=2007 |publisher=Daiwa Shobō |isbn=978-4-479-39166-1 |location=Tōkyō |oclc=237474432}}</ref> From these, it is presumed that the deity enshrined at Tsukiyomi is the moon god who also governs the tides of the sea, and is enshrined by the ancient Iki clan. There is also a theory that Tsukiyomi has another divine aspect as the god of turtle, due to the fact that Iki clan is a major producer of turtle shells.<ref name=":2" />
Moreover, in the April article of the 3rd year of Emeperor Kenzo of ''Nihon Shoki'', there is a description of "Sun God" enshrined in Tsukiyomi by Kenchoku Tsushima, but it originated from a deity distinct from Amaterasu. In the same article, it is recorded that this sun god, like the god of the moon, is the decedent of Takamimusubi.
